µC0Goodbye Gone!

µC4I am tired, tired of trying to help the scene survive, my spirit has lost his motivation to keep on writing for the Amiga scene. The Amiga scene where nothing goes easy anymore, nothing comes naturally, and this is what I hate the most. One year ago, things went automatically, things went the way they should.

There was feedback, there was power, there was an atmosphere that made you work for the scene. There was commitment. But nowadays, it seems that it all fades away, and along with that is my love for the scene.

Unfortunately, cause I always loved the scene and the people in it. But things go the wrong way, and they have been going the wrong way for several years. And nothing could change that. And when I say nothing I mean nothing.

It`s a like when you were a kid and you got a new toy, after a while you loose interest in that toy and you need a new one, or simply put it in the closet and wait new motivation to play with it again. It`s like having a new car, the first months you are careful and you wash and polish it once or twice a week, but later it just gets normal and you loose your love for the car also.

I mean, why should I (and I think that other sceners feel this the same way) force myself to be active without having the motivation and love anymore. This scene seems to be filled with sceners that do not have the motivation anymore to put love and inspiration into their work. And this is where I draw the line.

All these years of hard work and giving it all to the scene has not paid of, so we failed, and I make my conclusions. All those hours which I spend on my room behind the Amiga getting hurt in my eyes of staring at the screen, all that money I spend on equipment and software which gave me so much pleasure it has all ended right here.
I had a terrific time in the scene, and I want to thank all sceners who have crossed my road in a good or a bad way for the great time I had. Maybe it was wiser to quit earlier with the scene, but my urge to survive kept me floating for a while and finally a big rock was put in my hands.

For a while Zito and Ghandy kept me alive by let me join in the their JP issues, which was great and I am proud to have served the readers of JP by writing my articles on my own way, whether you liked them or not. It was great to see my name on the Eurochart, as a swapper and later as an editor.

Great was the time when I came home from school and saw that there were a lot of packages waiting for me at the table with new wares. And probable when Internet was not realized this would still be the way. Internet changed the scene into an impersonal atmosphere in my eyes.

Too much has happened to write it all down, and I wonder if you are waiting for that, but you can always mail me for some more info if you wish.


So for all you sceners out there, thank you for the time we had, and live long and prosper.






